text: Retinitis Pigmentosa 2 is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, which means it is caused by a single gene on the X chromosome and typically affects males more severely than females due to the way the X chromosome is inherited. It has been defined as "a retinitis pigmentosa that has_material_basis_in mutation in the RP2 gene on chromosome Xp11.3." It also has an exact synonym of RP2.

Retinitis pigmentosa 24 is a type of x-linked monogenic disease. X-linked means that the gene for this condition is located on the X chromosome, and males are more likely to have affected individuals because they only have one copy of the X chromosome. Monogenic diseases are those caused by mutations in a single gene. Retinitis pigmentosa is a type of degenerative eye disease that affects the retina, causing progressive vision loss.
Retinitis pigmentosa 34 is a specific type of retinitis pigmentosa that has a genetic basis in variation at the chromosome region Xq28. This condition may also be referred to as RP34.

Retinitis pigmentosa y linked refers to a specific type of retinitis pigmentosa that has a genetic basis and is passed down through generations. It specifically involves a variation on the Y chromosome, which is one of the two sex chromosomes in humans, with the other being the X chromosome. This means that only males are affected by this specific type of retinitis pigmentosa, as they have only one copy of the Y chromosome. Females, on the other hand, typically have two copies of the X chromosome and may express a different form of the disease or be completely asymptomatic.

Retinitis pigmentosa is a condition that affects the retina and causes progressive vision loss. It can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the disease. There are different types of retinitis pigmentosa, including those that are associated with other medical conditions such as situs inversus. Situs inversus is a condition where the internal organs are positioned in the opposite direction to their usual location in the body. It can be associated with certain genetic disorders, including retinitis pigmentosa.

Dominant pericentral pigmentary retinopathy is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means that it can be passed down through families and tends to affect multiple family members. It has a material basis in the genetic inheritance, but not everyone with a genetic predisposition will develop the condition.
It is characterized by pigmentary retinal degeneration, specifically involving the pericentral area of the retina, leading to blindness in the sixth and seventh decades of life for those affected.

Late adult onset retinitis pigmentosa is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means it is passed down through genes from parents to their offspring. It typically starts during late onset or middle age and can cause symptoms such as vision loss and night blindness. It has been described as senile retinitis pigmentosa, but this term may not be accurate as it can occur at any age.

Autosomal recessive pericentral pigmentary retinopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the retina. It is characterized by pigmentary retinal degeneration, which occurs due to the inheritance of certain genes from both parents. This condition typically affects infants and has a slower rate of progression than other forms of retinopathy.

Dilated cardiomyopathy is a condition where the heart becomes enlarged and has difficulty pumping blood effectively. It can lead to various complications if not properly managed, such as heart failure and arrhythmias. In general, CMD1L is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that having one copy of the mutated gene is usually sufficient for the disease to develop.

Treatment options for Dilated Cardiomyopathy 1k may include medications, lifestyle changes, and surgical procedures to improve heart function and quality of life.

Dilated cardiomyopathy 1b is a condition that affects the heart muscle and causes it to become weakened and enlarged. It is one of several types of dilated cardiomyopathy, which are characterized by a decrease in the heart's ability to pump blood efficiently. Dilated cardiomyopathy 1b is also known as familial dilated cardiomyopathy and can be inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent has the condition, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. The condition is caused by mutations in the MYH7 gene, which encodes the beta-myosin heavy chain protein. This protein is essential for the proper functioning of the heart muscle. When this protein is mutated, it can cause the heart to become larger and weaker over time, leading to the symptoms associated with dilated cardiomyopathy 1b.

Dilated Cardiomyopathy type 1R (DCM1R) is a subtype of Dilated Cardiomyopathy that has a strong genetic component, with mutations in the ACTC1 gene on chromosome 15q14 being the most common cause. DCM1R can be distinguished from other types of DCM by its genetic basis and specific clinical features. Patients with DCM1R often present at an earlier age than those with other subtypes of DCM, and may have larger left ventricles and thicker walls in the heart. The disease can progress slowly or rapidly, depending on the severity of the mutation and the overall health of the individual.

Treatment options for DCM1R typically include medications to improve heart function and reduce symptoms, such as beta-blockers, calcium channel blockers, and ACE inhibitors. In some cases, a pacemaker may be implanted to regulate abnormal heart rhythms. Surgical interventions, such as cardiac transplantation or the placement of an assist device, may also be considered for advanced cases.

It is important for individuals with DCM1R to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop a comprehensive treatment plan that addresses their specific needs and helps manage the disease effectively.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 45 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that has a material basis in mutations in the NT5C2 gene on chromosome 10q24. It is also known by several other names, including SPG45, SPG65, and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 45 or type 65.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 46, also known as SPG46 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 46, is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive muscular weakness and stiffness in the lower limbs. It is caused by mutations in the GBA2 gene on chromosome 9p13. The exact synonyms for this condition include hereditary spastic paraplegia, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 46, and SPG46. This disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 47 (SPG47) is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by progressive muscle stiffness and weakness in the lower limbs. It is caused by mutations in the AP4B1 gene on chromosome 1p13. The exact synonyms for SPG47 include CPSQ5, SPG47, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 47, and spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy 5.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 48, also known as SPG48 or autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 48, is a genetic disorder caused by mutations in the AP5Z1 gene on chromosome 7p22.1. It is one of many types of hereditary spastic paraplegias, which are characterized by progressive muscle stiffness and weakness in the lower limbs.
Hereditary spastic paraplegia 48 is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. Symptoms typically begin in childhood or adolescence and can worsen over time. There is no cure for hereditary spastic paraplegia 48, but treatment options may include physical therapy, medications, and assistive devices to help manage symptoms.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 49, also known as SPG49 or autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 49, is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive muscle stiffness and weakness in the lower extremities. It is caused by mutations in the TECPR2 gene on chromosome 14q32. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that to develop the disease, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. There is no cure for hereditary spastic paraplegia 49, but physical therapy and other forms of treatment can help manage the symptoms.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 50 is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by weakness and stiffness in the lower limbs. It is caused by mutations in the AP4M1 gene on chromosome 7q22.1, which encodes the adaptor protein complex 4. This condition is also known as AP-4 deficiency syndrome or SPG50 and is one of several types of hereditary spastic paraplegia.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 51, also known as CPSQ4 and SPG51, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by weakness and stiffness in the legs. It is caused by mutations in the AP4E1 gene located on chromosome 15q21. The condition has material basis in some cases due to this mutation. It is also known as autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 51 and spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy 4, among other names.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 52, also known as CPSQ6 and SPG52, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by weakness in the legs and lower body, which can lead to difficulty walking or even complete paralysis. The condition is caused by mutations in the AP4S1 gene on chromosome 14q12. It has an exact synonym of spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy 6 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 52.

hereditary spastic paraplegia 53 is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia that has material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is defined by mutation in the VPS37A gene on chromosome 8p22. It can also be referred to as SPG53 or autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 53.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 54, also known as SPG54 or autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 54, is a genetic disorder that affects the nervous system. It is caused by mutations in the DDHD2 gene, which is located on chromosome 8p11. This condition leads to the gradual development of spastic paralysis, which can cause stiffness, weakness, and a loss of reflexes in the lower limbs. It typically presents in adulthood and affects males and females equally. There is no cure for this condition, but physical therapy, medications, and other treatments can help manage the symptoms.
Hereditary spastic paraplegia 55 (SPG55) is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 56 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, characterized by weakness and stiffness in the legs. It is caused by mutations in the CYP2U1 gene on chromosome 4q25. The condition has an exact synonym called SPG56, which refers to a hereditary spastic paraplegia that has material basis in mutation of this specific gene. Additionally, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 56 is another exact synonym for the disease, emphasizing its autosomal recessive inheritance pattern and type 56 designation.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 57 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by the presence of mutation in the TFG gene on chromosome 3q12, leading to abnormalities in the development and functioning of the peripheral nervous system. This can result in weakness and stiffness of the legs, which are known as spastic paraplegia. It is also known as SPG57 or autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 57.

hereditary spastic paraplegia 5a is a type of autosomal recessive disease.
hereditary spastic paraplegia 5a is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia.

hereditary spastic paraplegia 5a has exact synonym autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 5A.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 6 is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by rapidly progressive and severe spastic paraplegia, and has material basis in mutation in the NIPA1 gene on chromosome 15q11.2. It has exact synonyms such as FSP3, SPG6, autosomal dominant familial spastic paraplegia type 3, autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 6, and autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia type 6.
Hereditary spastic paraplegia 61 is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 62, also known as SPG62 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 62 (ARSP62), is a genetic disorder that affects movement and causes stiffness in the lower limbs. It is caused by mutations in the ERLIN1 gene, which is located on chromosome 10q24. This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the disease, a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene, one from each parent. There is currently no cure for hereditary spastic paraplegia 62, but physical therapy and other forms of treatment can help manage the symptoms.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 63, also known as SPG63, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder. It is characterized by the presence of mutations in the AMPD2 gene on chromosome 1p13. This leads to defects in mitochondrial function and accumulation of harmful substances in the body, resulting in motor symptoms such as weakness and stiffness in the lower limbs. It is important to note that hereditary spastic paraplegia 63 has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and shares exact synonyms with other terms such as SPG63, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 63, and spastic paraplegia 63.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 64 (SPG64) is a genetic disorder that is caused by mutations in the ENTPD1 gene, which is located on chromosome 10q24. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that to develop the disease, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent.
Symptoms typically begin in childhood and include spasticity (stiffness) in the legs, muscle weakness, and difficulty with coordination and balance. The severity of the symptoms can vary widely among individuals affected by the disorder. There is no cure for SPG64, but physical therapy and other forms of treatment can help manage the symptoms.
Hereditary spastic paraplegia 7 is a type of autosomal recessive disease.
Hereditary spastic paraplegia 72a, also known as SPG72, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that has material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the REEP2 gene on chromosome 5q31.2.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 73, also known as SPG73 or autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia type 73, is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles and can cause weakness in the legs. It is caused by mutations in the CPT1C gene on chromosome 19q13. This condition is passed down through families and typically presents in adulthood. Treatment options include physical therapy, medication, and assistive devices to help manage symptoms.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 74 (SPG74) is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by the presence of a mutation in the IBA57 gene, which is located on chromosome 1q42. The exact synonyms for SPG74 include hereditary spastic paraplegia and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 74. This condition affects muscle control and movement in the lower limbs, leading to a characteristic gait known as "spastic paraplegia."

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 75, also known as SPG75 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 75, is a genetic disorder that is caused by mutations in the MAG gene on chromosome 19q13. It is one of several types of hereditary spastic paraplegias, which are characterized by progressive weakness and stiffness in the legs. SPG75 affects about 1 in 40,000 individuals and can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern. Symptoms typically begin in childhood and can include difficulty walking, muscle stiffness, and spasticity. There is no cure for this condition, but physical therapy, medications, and other treatments can help manage the symptoms.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 76 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means it is caused by the inheritance of a single copy of the mutated gene from each parent. The mutation in the CAPN1 gene on chromosome 11q13 leads to the development of this condition. It is also known as SPG76 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 76.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 77 is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by the inheritance of a mutated FARS2 gene on chromosome 6p25. It has the exact synonyms SPG77 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 77, which is a hereditary condition that results from the passing down of an abnormal gene from generation to generation. This can lead to problems with movement and coordination, and it usually affects the legs. It is also known as spastic paraplegia type 77, and it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 8 (SPG8) is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by progressive spasticity, weakness and atrophy of the leg muscles. The condition is caused by mutations in the KIAA0196 gene on chromosome 8q24. SPG8 has exact synonyms such as autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 8 (ADSP8) and hereditary spastic paraplegia type 8 (HSF8).

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 9a is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by the inheritance of a single copy of the ALDH18A1 gene on chromosome 10q24, which encodes an enzyme involved in the metabolism of alcohol and other toxins. This leads to a deficiency in these enzymatic activities, which can result in various symptoms such as spastic paraplegia (difficulty walking), cataracts, short stature, and skeletal abnormalities. The condition is also known by several other names including AD-SPG9A, SPG9A, autosomal dominant complex spastic paraplegia type 9A, and cataracts with motor neuronopathy, short stature and skeletal abnormalities.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 9b is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the nervous system. It is characterized by weakness and stiffness in the legs, which can make it difficult to move around. The condition is caused by mutations in the ALDH18A1 gene on chromosome 10q24. It is also known as SPG9B or autosomal recessive complex spastic paraplegia type 9B, and can be inherited from parents who carry the gene.

Usher syndrome type 1 is a genetic disorder that affects the retina, inner ear, and hearing. It is characterized by congenital deafness (also known as profound deafness), vestibular dysfunction, and early onset of retinitis pigmentosa. The condition is caused by mutations in the USH1 gene, which provides instructions for making a protein called harmonin that is important for maintaining normal functioning of sensory cells in the inner ear and retina. As a result, people with Usher syndrome type 1 have difficulty hearing and balance, leading to problems with speech, language, and mobility. Treatment options are limited, but early intervention can help manage symptoms and improve quality of life for individuals affected by this disorder.

Usher syndrome type 2, also known as USH2, is a form of Usher syndrome characterized by mild to severe congenital hearing impairment, normal vestibular function, and the eventual development of retinitis pigmentosa.

Usher Syndrome Type 3, also known as USH3, is a form of Usher Syndrome that affects both hearing and vision. It typically begins with progressive hearing loss during late childhood, followed by variable vestibular dysfunction, and the onset of retinitis pigmentosa in the second decade of life.

Retinitis pigmentosa deafness syndrome is a type of Usher Syndrome, which is characterized by the progressive degeneration of vision and hearing. It is an autosomal dominant disease, meaning that it can be passed down through family genes and tends to affect multiple family members. The condition has a material basis in mutations in the MTTS2 gene, which are located in the mitochondrial genome.

Usher syndrome type Ic is a form of Usher syndrome that has a genetic basis. Specifically, it is caused by mutations in the USH1C gene, which is located on chromosome 11p15. This condition is also known as Usher syndrome type I Acadian variety and Usher syndrome type IC. It is characterized by a combination of hearing loss and vision problems, including retinitis pigmentosa and photophobia.

Usher syndrome type 1d is a form of Usher syndrome, which is characterized by deafness and blindness. It is caused by mutations in the CDH23 gene on chromosome 10q22. The condition can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner or through compound heterozygosity. It is also known as Usher syndrome type ID and has the exact synonym USH1D.

Usher syndrome type 1F (USH1F) is a form of Usher syndrome, which is a group of genetic disorders that primarily affect the hearing and vision. USH1F specifically refers to a subtype of Usher syndrome where there is a mutation in the PCDH15 gene on chromosome 10q. This condition can result in both retinitis pigmentosa (a progressive degeneration of the retina) and hearing loss. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. Other synonyms for USH1F include Usher syndrome type IF.

Usher syndrome type 1e (USH1E) is a subtype of Usher syndrome, which is a group of genetic disorders that primarily affect the auditory and visual systems. USH1E specifically refers to a form of Usher syndrome where there is a mutation in the USH1E gene on chromosome 21q21. This mutation leads to the gradual loss of hearing and vision, often beginning in childhood or early adolescence. Other types of Usher syndrome are caused by different gene mutations, but all share some common features such as hearing loss, balance problems, and retinitis pigmentosa (a degenerative condition of the retina).

Usher syndrome type 1g, also known as USH1G or Usher syndrome type IG, is a form of Usher syndrome that results from mutations in the USH1G gene located on chromosome 17q25. It is characterized by hearing and vision loss, typically beginning in childhood. The condition can also include additional symptoms such as balance problems, muscle weakness, and kidney issues. Usher syndrome type 1g is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Usher Syndrome Type 1H, also known as Usher Syndrome Type IH, is a type of Usher Syndrome that is characterized by hearing and vision loss. This condition is caused by mutations in the USH1H gene, which is located on the q22-q23 region of chromosome 15. It is one of three types of Usher Syndrome, which are a group of genetic disorders that primarily affect the sense of hearing and vision.

Usher Syndrome Type 1J is a form of Usher Syndrome that is caused by mutations in the CIB2 gene on chromosome 15q24. It is characterized by deafness and blindness, which typically begin in childhood or adolescence. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning that it is inherited from both parents and can affect any race. The exact synonyms for Usher Syndrome Type 1J are Usher Syndrome Type IJ and USH1J.

Usher syndrome type 1k, also known as Usher syndrome type IK, is a form of Usher syndrome that has a genetic basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by blindness and hearing loss. The specific location on the chromosome where this variation occurs is 10p11.21-q21.1. This condition is also known as Usher syndrome type 1 that has a material basis in variation at this specific location on the chromosome.

Usher syndrome type 2a is a form of Usher syndrome that is characterized by moderate to severe sensorineural hearing loss and progressive retinitis pigmentosa, which are both due to mutations in the USH2A gene on chromosome 1q41. The condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, meaning that it is inherited from a parent who carries one copy of the faulty gene (heterozygous) and can be passed on to offspring. Usher syndrome type 2a is also known as USH2A or Usher syndrome type IIA.

Usher syndrome type 2c, also known as USH2C or Usher syndrome type IIC, is a type of Usher syndrome that is caused by mutations in the ADGRV1 gene on chromosome 5q14. It is characterized by hearing and vision loss, typically starting in childhood. This condition can also cause balance problems and an increased risk of developing other health issues related to the heart and kidneys. Usher syndrome type 2c is a genetic disorder that is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent, to develop the condition. It can also be caused by compound heterozygous mutations, where a person has two different mutations in the same gene. Overall, Usher syndrome type 2c is a rare genetic disorder that affects many parts of the body and can significantly impact a person's quality of life.

Usher syndrome type 2D, also known as USH2D or Usher syndrome type IID, is a form of Usher syndrome caused by mutations in the WHRN gene on chromosome 9q32. It is characterized by progressive hearing and vision loss, often beginning in childhood. The severity of symptoms can vary greatly among individuals affected by this condition. Some may experience only mild hearing and vision impairment, while others may have more severe forms of the disease that lead to deafness and blindness. It is important to note that Usher syndrome type 2D has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, which means that it is inherited from both parents and can be passed down through generations.

Usher Syndrome Type 3a is a type of Usher Syndrome that has a genetic basis and is characterized by progressive hearing and vision loss. It is distinguished from Usher Syndrome Type 3b, which also has a genetic basis but is not necessarily related to the CLRN1 gene on chromosome 3q25.
Usher Syndrome Type 3a is also known as USH3A and Usher Syndrome Type IIIA. It is important to note that both Usher Syndrome Type 3a and Usher Syndrome Type 3b can cause significant disability and may require specialized medical care and support for individuals affected by them.

Usher syndrome type 3b, also known as USH3B or Usher syndrome type IIIB, is a subtype of Usher syndrome that is characterized by hearing and vision loss due to mutations in the HARS gene on chromosome 5q31. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that it requires the inheritance of two copies of the faulty gene (one from each parent) for its development.

Xeroderma pigmentosum (XP) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the skin, eyes, and internal organs, causing premature aging of the skin and an increased risk of developing various types of cancer. There are eight subtypes of XP, with Xeroderma Pigmentosum Group C being one of them. It is characterized by a mutation in the XPC gene on chromosome 3p25, which results in an increased propensity to develop malignant melanoma. The condition has synonyms such as XP group C, XP3, XPC, XPCC, and xeroderma pigmentosum III.

text:
Xeroderma pigmentosum group D, also known as XP-D or XPD, is a type of xeroderma pigmentosum characterized by a deficiency in the ability to repair DNA damage caused by UV radiation. This condition is typically inherited in an autosomal recessive manner and results from mutations in the ERCC2 gene located on chromosome 19q13.
Xeroderma pigmentosum group D is one of eight subtypes of xeroderma pigmentosum, each with specific genetic differences that affect their severity and clinical presentation. Other subtypes include XP-A, XP-B, XP-C, XP-G, XP-V, and XP-VI.
In addition to skin and eye damage caused by UV radiation, individuals with xeroderma pigmentosum are also at an increased risk of developing skin cancer, particularly melanoma. Treatment options for xeroderma pigmentosum may include the use of sunscreens with high SPF, protective clothing, and avoiding prolonged exposure to UV radiation.

Xeroderma pigmentosum group E, also known as XP-E or XP5, is a type of xeroderma pigmentosum characterized by a mild phenotype and is caused by homozygous mutation in the DDB2 gene on chromosome 11p11. It has exact synonyms such as XP group E, XP5, XPE, and xeroderma pigmentosum V.

xeroderma pigmentosum variant type (XPV) is a subtype of xeroderma pigmentosum, characterized by normal DNA excision repair but defective postreplication repair due to mutations in the POLH gene on chromosome 6p21.1. It has the same symptoms as other types of XP but can be distinguished through genetic testing. It is also known as photosensitivity with defective DNA synthesis and xeroderma pigmentosum with normal DNA repair rates.

Xeroderma pigmentosum group F, also known as XP6 or XPF, is a milder form of xeroderma pigmentosum characterized by later onset and less severe symptoms compared to other forms of the condition. It is caused by mutations in the ERCC4 gene located on chromosome 16p13. This genetic disorder makes individuals highly sensitive to UV radiation, leading to an increased risk of skin cancer.

Xeroderma pigmentosum (XP) is a rare genetic disorder that causes severe skin damage from the sun. It is caused by mutations in the DNA repair gene ERCC5, which is located on chromosome 13q33. There are eight types of XP, with Group G being one of them. People with XP have a defect in their ability to repair UV-damaged DNA, making them highly sensitive to the sun and increasing their risk of skin cancer.

Xeroderma pigmentosum group B (XPB) is a type of Xeroderma Pigmentosum. It is characterized by a mutation in the ERCC3 gene on chromosome 2q14. XPB has the same clinical features as other types of XP, including severe skin and eye damage due to increased sensitivity to UV radiation. Like all types of XP, it can be passed down through generations and is typically diagnosed in childhood.

Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 1 is a genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and cartilage in the body. It is caused by mutations in the PEX7 gene on chromosome 6q23.3, which encodes an essential protein for peroxisome biogenesis. The condition can cause short stature, bone deformities, and other skeletal abnormalities. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. There are no current treatments for rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 1, but management may involve medications and other supportive care to address the symptoms.

Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 2 is a genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and joints. It is caused by a mutation in the GNPAT gene on chromosome 1q42.2, which encodes an enzyme involved in the metabolism of glycerol and phosphate. This leads to an accumulation of dihydroxyacetonephosphate (DHAP) in the mitochondria, resulting in impaired energy production and skeletal abnormalities.

Symptoms of rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 2 include short stature, bone deformities, and joint problems. The severity of the condition can vary greatly depending on the specific gene mutation and the individual's overall health. Treatment may involve medications to manage pain and improve mobility, as well as physical therapy to help maintain muscle strength and flexibility. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to correct bone deformities.

Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial for managing the symptoms of rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 2 and improving quality of life. Genetic counseling can also help individuals understand the risks and implications of the condition for themselves and their families.

Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 3 is a genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and cartilage. It is caused by mutations in the AGPS gene, which is located on chromosome 2q31.2. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to have full-blown symptoms, a person would need to inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent).

Symptoms may include short stature, bowed legs, and an irregular shape to the bones. The condition can also lead to hearing loss and vision problems. Treatment options are limited and mainly focus on managing the symptoms rather than curing the underlying condition. It's important for people with this disorder to work closely with their healthcare providers to ensure they receive appropriate care and support.

rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 5 is a specific form of rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata, which is characterized by abnormal development of the bones in the hand and foot. It has been linked to mutations in the PEX5 gene on chromosome 12p13.31, and can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. Another name for this condition is Rcdp5.
posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the corneal endothelium, leading to corneal opacification and vision loss if left untreated. It has a prevalence of around 1 in 500,000 individuals and is most commonly found in Middle Eastern populations. The condition is caused by mutations in the COL8A2 gene on chromosome 1p34.3.

posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy 3 is a type of monogenic disease.
posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy 3 is a type of posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy.

Polycystic kidney disease 1, also known as autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD), is a genetic disorder characterized by the growth of multiple cysts in the kidneys. It is caused by mutations in the PKD1 gene, which is located on chromosome 16p13.3. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a person has an 50% chance of inheriting the disorder if one of their parents carries the gene.

There are two types of polycystic kidney disease: ADPKD and autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease (ARPKD). ADPKD is more common and usually occurs later in life, while ARPKD typically presents in infancy or childhood. PKD1 mutations are responsible for ADPKD, while ARPKD is caused by mutations in the PKHD1 gene.

Polycystic kidney disease can lead to chronic kidney failure and may require dialysis or a kidney transplant. Regular monitoring of blood pressure, protein levels, and imaging studies (such as ultrasounds) are important for early detection and management of the condition.

Polycystic Kidney Disease 2, also known as Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Kidney Disease (ADPKD2), is a genetic disorder that affects the kidneys. It is characterized by the presence of numerous cysts in the kidneys, which can lead to enlargement and eventual failure of the organ. ADPKD2 is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the faulty gene is enough to cause the disease. The PKD2 gene is located on chromosome 4q22.1, and mutations in this gene are responsible for the development of cysts in the kidneys.

There are two types of polycystic kidney disease: ADPKD1 and ADPKD2. While both types can cause similar symptoms such as high blood pressure, pain, and swelling in the legs and feet, they differ in their genetic causes and the age at which the disease typically develops.

Treatment options for ADPKD2 include medications to manage high blood pressure, dietary restrictions, and regular monitoring of kidney function. In some cases, surgery may be recommended to remove affected kidneys or alleviate pressure on the cysts. It is important to work closely with a healthcare professional to develop an appropriate treatment plan tailored to individual needs.

Polycystic kidney disease 3, also known as PKD3, is a type of autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease. It is characterized by the presence of numerous cysts in the kidneys, which can lead to enlargement and eventual failure of the organs.
PKD3 is caused by mutations in the GANAB gene on chromosome 11q12.3. This inherited genetic variation increases the risk of developing PKD and the severity of the disease.
There are no specific symptoms associated with PKD3, but it can cause kidney pain, blood in the urine, frequent urination, and high blood pressure. If left untreated, PKD can lead to end-stage renal disease (ESRD) and require dialysis or a kidney transplant.
It is essential for individuals with a family history of PKD to undergo regular screenings to detect the early stages of the disease and receive appropriate treatment.

Autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease (ARPKD) is a type of polycystic kidney disease that is caused by mutations in the PKHD1 gene. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that to develop the condition, an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent.
ARPKD typically presents in infancy and childhood and can lead to kidney failure if left untreated. Treatment options include medications to manage high blood pressure, dietary changes, and kidney transplantation. It is important for individuals with ARPKD to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop a comprehensive treatment plan tailored to their specific needs.

Congenital stationary night blindness autosomal dominant 1 is a type of congenital stationary night blindness, which refers to a group of inherited retinal disorders characterized by severe and permanent night blindness. This condition is caused by mutations in genes responsible for the production of rhodopsin, a protein essential for vision in low-light conditions.

Autosomal dominant inheritance means that the gene responsible for this condition can be passed down from one generation to another through either parent, with a 50% chance of passing it on to each offspring. This type of inheritance is seen in families with a history of night blindness and other eye-related problems.

Congenital stationary night blindness autosomal dominant 1 specifically refers to the presence of mutations in the RHO gene, which is located on chromosome 3q22.1. These mutations lead to a deficiency or absence of functional rhodopsin, resulting in difficulty seeing in low light conditions and limited ability to adapt to darkness.

Other synonyms for this condition include CSNBAD1 and rhodopsin-related congenital stationary night blindness.

Congenital stationary night blindness autosomal dominant 2 is a type of congenital stationary night blindness characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the PDE6B gene on chromosome 4p16. It also has exact synonyms such as CSNBAD2 and Rambusch type congenital stationary night blindness.
